We have decided we want and need to recognize our outstanding students at Varnum High School, so every month the HS teachers will submit applications for a Student of the Month. Covid put a little kink in our plans to start school this week, but we didn‚Äôt let it stop us from recognizing an outstanding student!

August Varnum High School Student of the Month is Laura McCutcheon!

Laura is a very active Whippet in softball, basketball, cheer, and 4-H. She is also attending Gordon Cooper Cosmetology School and concurrently enrolled at Seminole State College. Laura is a consistent honor roll student and a member of the Varnum National Honor Society.

Laura‚Äôs teachers have called her ‚Äúrespectful, independent, and responsible‚Äù. She is also known to have a ‚Äúgreat heart for anyone.‚Äù

Congratulations Laura!

-ATTENTION SEMINOLE NATION TRIBAL MEMBERS-
The Seminole Nation Judgment Fund - Clothing Program application has been "Revised". Please submit the "REVISED" CLOTHING PROGRAM APPLICATION. The Funding for Clothing Program remains the same - $100.00 per Tribal enrolled children ages 4 years old (Pre-K) through 19 years (High School Senior)

Applications for download are now available on the Seminole Nation of Oklahoma Website (TRIBAL SERVICES tab, JUDGEMENT FUND drop down menu) If you do not have access to the Website, please call the office at (405) 382-0549 and we will mail the application(s) directly to you.

As of this date, the SN Judgment Fund office is CLOSED TO THE PUBLIC.

PLEASE mail ALL Clothing applications Starting August 1, 2020. Again, please download and mail in the "Revised" application.

The SN Clothing Program is from August 1, 2020 to September 30 of each year.

The Gates Scholarship (TGS) is a highly selective, last-dollar scholarship for outstanding, minority, high school seniors from low-income households. Each year, the scholarship is awarded to 300 of these student leaders, with the intent of helping them realize their maximum potential.
Scholars will receive funding for the full cost of attendance* that is not already covered by other financial aid and the expected family contribution, as determined by the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA), or the methodology used by a Scholar‚Äôs college or university.

Varnum Schools is humbled to have received this grant as well as the $50,000 CARES ACT earlier in the summer. This one was announced today by @Joy Hofmeister our State Superintendent of Schools. This will enable our district to continue to meet the needs of our families during this unprecedented time. This grant allows us to offer 100 hotspots at an extremely discounted rate to us, which we in turn provide free to our families! This will be a significant savings for our school while continuing to provide the best education around.

Varnum Schools is humbled to have received this grant as well as the $50,000 CARES ACT earlier in the summer. This one was announced today by @Joy Hofmeister our State Superintendent of Schools. This grant allows us to offer 100 hotspots at an extremely discounted rate to us, which we in turn provide free to our families! This will be a significant savings for our school while continuing to provide the best education around.

post_text:
‚ÄºÔ∏èüëÄParentsüëÄ‚ÄºÔ∏è

We know we all have a love/hate relationship with the GroupMe App, but I believe it has honestly been a huge help to all of us during this time. We plan to continue using the App and are working on getting all the class titles moved up to the 20-21 classes (last year 7th will now say 20-21 8th, etc).

That being said we have found one small glitch. If a parent or teacher chooses or accidentally takes themself out of the group we can no longer add that person back to the group under that number. We know there will be a few groups we might have to redo because of this issue, but we will wait until after enrollment and see where we are with our GroupMe lists before we do that.

That being said, PLEASE do NOT REMOVE YOURSELF from a GroupMe. If you want to be removed please contact someone within administration and we will remove you. If we remove you, you can be re-added at a later date if you need to be.

Thank You!

post_text:
Attn: Any Varnum High School students that are interested in taking Driver‚Äôs Ed this Summer.
The following criteria must be met to meet the legal requirements of the State Dept of Ed and the Dept of Public Safety:
*Student must be at least 15 yrs of age by June 30. (Any student whose 15th birthday falls between June 30 and July 12 can contact Coach Hadley and he will check on possible clearance).
*Must be able and willing to complete a Distance Learning Course (the classroom portion of the course) in an effective manner and meet the curriculum deadlines set by the instructor.

There is a $100 fee, payable to Varnum School, that is to be turned in to Stacey before completion documents will be released. Note: Payment DOES NOT have to be made to start the course, but is required to get the documents needed for permits or licenses.
(If needed, Payment/installment arrangements can be made by contacting Stacey).

post_text:
This is Teacher Appreciation Week and I want to take a minute and brag on my teachers at Varnumüíö! I believe we have a school full of exceptional teachers! Teachers who will go out of their way to help ‚Äútheir kids‚Äù learn, grow and yes, have fun. Our teachers put in many hours of extra time so Varnum Students can have experiences many districts can‚Äôt or don‚Äôt offer. Our teachers love their students like their own. They celebrate successes, laugh at memories, and cry during disappointments. They give high fives, hugs and yes, sometimes ‚Äúthe look‚Äù when needed, but it all comes from the heart.

Not one teacher griped or complained about ‚Äúdistance learning‚Äù. Not one grumbled about starting one way and switching directions the next week. They all put on their capes and did the very best they could for their students! They miss them; they worry about them; they love them (yes even the ones that try their patience ü§™)!

Please take a minute this week and reach out to a teacher or two who has touched your life...I promise it will make their day!üíöüíöüíö

March 27, 2020

Attention Varnum Parents/Student:
We have been granted a new waiver stating that we may now serve multiple days meals in a single day. Therefore, in an effort to do our part to prevent spreading the COVID-19 Virus and limiting exposure, we will start next week distributing meals only on Mondays and Wednesdays. Whether you are picking your meals up or they are being delivered, you will receive both Monday and Tuesdays meals on Monday from 10-11:30 and Wednesday-Fridays meals on Wednesday from 10-11:30 each week. If you have any questions, you may contact the Superintendent's Office and leave a message for Stacey Benard @ (405) 382-1408 EXT: 101.

post_text:
MESSAGE FROM THE SUPERINTENDENT:
RE: COVID-19
As you know, the Coronavirus Pandemic is a very fluid situation at this time. The state of Oklahoma is now under a state of emergency and it is my understanding that no gatherings larger than 50 people are recommended.
As it stands now, we are scheduled to return to class Monday, March 23rd. I have made no plans past that date while we wait for clearer communication either nationally or from the state.
I ask that no students, parents, etc., come to the school grounds this week. There will be no games, practices, leadership events, etc. until further notice. We will undergo a deep cleaning before we return to school.
Please enjoy your spring break!
I will notify you if and when something changes in regards to further closing dates.
Wash your hands!

post_text:
SENIORS:
In 2010, Carolyn established the Carolyn Watson Opportunities Scholarship to help individual students graduating from Oklahoma‚Äôs rural high schools. To qualify, students must attend high school in one of 62 rural Oklahoma counties, have financial need and have demonstrated academic ability based upon a minimum grade point average of 3.25. Starting in Fall 2019, the scholarship amount for students entering the program increased to up to $12,000 per academic year. Recipients may renew the scholarship each year for up to four academic years as long as they maintain a 3.0 grade point average. Students must be nominated by a teacher or community leader and demonstrate exceptional accomplishments outside of the normal classroom environment.

To apply for the Carolyn Watson Opportunities Scholarship, click https://occf.academicworks.com/opportunities/1224

post_text: Thank you to the Seminole Nation for the coverage. What an awesome job you guys did! So proud of the relationship we have developed with the Seminole Nation. Chief Greg Chilcoat, thank you for the shared vision for our kids!
shared_text:
Seminole Nation of Oklahoma
March 2, 2019 at 5:10 PM ¬∑

VARNUM LADY WHIPPETS WIN STATE!

OKLAHOMA CITY, OK- The Varnum Lady Whippets defeated the Hammon Lady Warriors 39-36.

Hammon kept the lead through out the game with Varnum staying close. Savannah Deatherage found herself with the play of the game to seal the championship with a lay-up and the foul.

Varnum Lady Whippets lead scorers were: Nakai Harjo 17, Savannah Deatherage 7, Brooklyn Biffle 6, and Morgan Kinsey with 4.
Varnum shot 31% from the field and 26% from three point range.

Delaney R. Pennock with the Call.
Jeremy Fultz Photog.
Varnum Public Schools

How exciting if this passes!!!

HB2018, introduced by Rep. Jon Echols & Rep. Monroe Nichols, provides eligibility for children of certified teachers to participate in the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program (OHLAP). Professional Oklahoma Educators supports this bill! We are working diligently at the Capitol to garner ‚Äúyes‚Äù votes.

HB2018 is on the agenda of the House Committee for Higher Education & Career Tech tomorrow at 3 p.m. Contact your local legislators to show your support! We will keep you posted!
